<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-18T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="666" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d666">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">816.00/882: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">San José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-18T11:00:00-06:00">June 18,
                                    1932—11 a.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 1:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>46. Referring to Department’s circular telegram dated June 17, 6 p.m.,
                            the <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Martínez</persName> manifesto was
                            published locally but occasioned little or no comment in or out of the
                            press. See my despatch No. 936 of June 16<note n="27" xml:id="d666fn27">Not printed.</note> which left by air-mail pouch this morning.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>